{"title_page": "Belmonte, Portugal", "text_new": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision\n| type            = municipality\n|official_name      = Belmonte\n|image_flag         = Pt-bmt1.png\n|image_shield       = BMT.png\n|image_skyline      = Villa de Belmonte.jpg\n|image_caption      = Belmonte\n|image_location     = LocalBelmonte.svg\n|region             = [[Centro Region, Portugal|Centro]]\n|CIM                = [[Beiras e Serra da Estrela]]\n|district           = [[Castelo Branco District|Castelo Branco]]\n|parishes           = \n|leader_name        = \n|leader_party       = \n|coordinates        = {{coord|40|21|N|7|21|W|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:100000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation          = \n|elevation_min      = \n|elevation_max      = \n|area_total         = 118.76\n|population_as_of   = 2011\n|population_total   = 6,859\n|patron             = \n|postal_code        = \n|area_code          = \n|website            = http://www.cm-belmonte.pt\n}}\n'''Belmonte''' ({{IPA-pt|\u02ccb\u025bl\u02c8m\u00f5t(\u0268)|-|Pt-pt Belmonte FF.ogg}}) is a [[concelho|municipality]] in the district of [[Castelo Branco (district)|Castelo Branco]], Portugal. The population in 2011 was 6,859,<ref name=ine>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115205227/http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 |date=November 15, 2016 }}</ref> in an area of 118.76&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |title=\u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds |access-date=2018-11-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105172426/http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |archive-date=2018-11-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Belmonte, Portugal.jpg|thumb|left|[[Castle of Belmonte]], Portugal.]]\n[[File:Centum Cellae (Colmeal da Torre), a parish of Belmonte.jpg|thumb|left|[[Centum Cellas]], originally a [[Roman Villa]] and later used as a military Outpost]]\n\nBelmonte is the birthplace of [[Pedro \u00c1lvares Cabral]], the navigator who discovered the [[Ilha de Vera Cruz|land of Vera Cruz]], now known as [[Brazil]]. Located in the Church of Santa Maria is the iconic statue of Nossa Senhora da Esperan\u00e7a (Our Lady of Hope), which Cabral took with him on his voyage. Until 1834, the statue was held by the Monastery of Nossa Senhora da Esperan\u00e7a. The former religious facility has been adapted for use as a modern boutique hotel.\n\nThe singer [[Zeca Afonso]] lived in Belmonte for part of his childhood, between 1938 and 1940. He lived with his uncle, the mayor of the town, whilst his parents were living in Mozambique.\n\nBelmonte is home to the last remaining community of [[marrano]]s in Portugal (known as the [[Belmonte Jews]]). They officially returned to [[Judaism]] in the 1970s and opened a [[synagogue]] in 1996.\n\nIn 2003, the [[American Sephardi Federation]] founded the Belmonte Project, designated to raise funds to acquire Judaic educational material and services for the community, which now numbers 160\u2013180. They opened a Jewish Museum of Belmonte ({{lang-pt|Museu Judaico de Belmonte}}) on 17 April 2005. In the summer of 2006, the American Sephardi Federation ceased to have the Belmonte Project under its auspices. {{Why?|date=November 2012}}\n\n==Geography==\nAdministratively, the municipality is divided into 4 civil parishes (''[[freguesia (Portugal)|freguesias]]''):<ref>{{cite web|title=Law nr. 11-A/2013, page 552 25|url=http://dre.pt/pdf1sdip/2013/01/01901/0000200147.pdf |accessdate=18 July 2014|author=''[[Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica]]''|language=Portuguese|format=pdf}}</ref>\n* Belmonte e Colmeal da Torre\n* Caria\n* Inguias\n* Ma\u00e7a\u00ednhas\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.cm-belmonte.pt Town Hall official website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110720010926/http://www.americansephardifederation.org/PDF/newsletter/spring2003.pdf American Sephardi Federation newsletter], Spring 2003\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/vitor107/sets/1707164/ Photos from Belmonte]\n*[http://www.forward.com/articles/12391/ After 500 Years in Hiding, Jews Bring Prosperity to Iberian Town]\n\n{{Municipalities of Castelo Branco}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Historic Jewish communities in Europe]]\n[[Category:Jewish Portuguese history]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Castelo Branco District]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Castelo Branco District]]\n\n\n{{CasteloBranco-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision\n| type            = municipality\n|official_name      = Belmonte\n|image_flag         = Pt-bmt1.png\n|image_shield       = BMT.png\n|image_skyline      = Villa de Belmonte.jpg\n|image_caption      = Belmonte\n|image_location     = LocalBelmonte.svg\n|region             = [[Centro Region, Portugal|Centro]]\n|CIM                = [[Beiras e Serra da Estrela]]\n|district           = [[Castelo Branco District|Castelo Branco]]\n|parishes           = \n|leader_name        = \n|leader_party       = \n|coordinates        = {{coord|40|21|N|7|21|W|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:100000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation          = \n|elevation_min      = \n|elevation_max      = \n|area_total         = 118.76\n|population_as_of   = 2011\n|population_total   = 6,859\n|patron             = \n|postal_code        = \n|area_code          = \n|website            = http://www.cm-belmonte.pt\n}}\n'''Belmonte''' ({{IPA-pt|\u02ccb\u025bl\u02c8m\u00f5t(\u0268)|-|Pt-pt Belmonte FF.ogg}}) is a [[concelho|municipality]] in the district of [[Castelo Branco (district)|Castelo Branco]], Portugal. The population in 2011 was 6,859,<ref name=ine>[http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115205227/http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0 |date=November 15, 2016 }}</ref> in an area of 118.76&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |title=\u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds |access-date=2018-11-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105172426/http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |archive-date=2018-11-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Belmonte, Portugal.jpg|thumb|left|[[Castle of Belmonte]], Portugal.]]\n[[File:Centum Cellae (Colmeal da Torre), a parish of Belmonte.jpg|thumb|left|[[Centum Cellas]], originally a [[Roman Villa]] and later used as a military Outpost]]\n\nBelmonte is the birthplace of [[Pedro \u00c1lvares Cabral]], the navigator who discovered the [[Ilha de Vera Cruz|land of Vera Cruz]], now known as [[Brazil]]. Located in the Church of Santa Maria is the iconic statue of Nossa Senhora da Esperan\u00e7a (Our Lady of Hope), which Cabral took with him on his voyage. Until 1834, the statue was held by the Monastery of Nossa Senhora da Esperan\u00e7a. The former religious facility has been adapted for use as a modern boutique hotel.\n\nThe singer [[Zeca Afonso]] lived in Belmonte for part of his childhood, between 1938 and 1940. He lived with his uncle, the mayor of the town, whilst his parents were living in Mozambique.\n\nBelmonte is home to the last remaining community of [[marrano]]s in Portugal (known as the [[Belmonte Jews]]). They officially returned to [[Judaism]] in the 1970s and opened a [[synagogue]] in 1996.\n\nIn 2003, the [[American Sephardi Federation]] founded the Belmonte Project, designated to raise funds to acquire Judaic educational material and services for the community, which now numbers 160\u2013180. They opened a Jewish Museum of Belmonte ({{lang-pt|Museu Judaico de Belmonte}}) on 17 April 2005. In the summer of 2006, the American Sephardi Federation ceased to have the Belmonte Project under its auspices. {{Why?|date=November 2012}}\n\n==Geography==\nAdministratively, the municipality is divided into 4 civil parishes (''[[freguesia (Portugal)|freguesias]]''):<ref>{{cite web|title=Law nr. 11-A/2013, page 552 25|url=http://dre.pt/pdf1sdip/2013/01/01901/0000200147.pdf |accessdate=18 July 2014|author=''[[Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica]]''|language=Portuguese|format=pdf}}</ref>\n* Belmonte e Colmeal da Torre\n* Caria\n* Inguias\n* Ma\u00e7a\u00ednhas\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.cm-belmonte.pt Town Hall official website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110720010926/http://www.americansephardifederation.org/PDF/newsletter/spring2003.pdf American Sephardi Federation newsletter], Spring 2003\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/vitor107/sets/1707164/ Photos from Belmonte]\n*[http://www.forward.com/articles/12391/ After 500 Years in Hiding, Jews Bring Prosperity to Iberian Town]\n\n{{Municipalities of Castelo Branco}}\n\n[[Category:Historic Jewish communities in Europe]]\n[[Category:Jewish Portuguese history]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Castelo Branco District]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Castelo Branco District]]\