emaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''X-Men: Days of Future Past''\n| 90% (320 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/x_men_days_of_future_past/ |title=X-Men: Days of Future Past |work=Rotten Tomatoes |publisher=Fandango Media |accessdate=November 21, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518122136/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/x_men_days_of_future_past/ |archive-date=May 18, 2016}}</ref>\n| 75 (43 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/x-men-days-of-future-past |title=X-Men: Days of Future Past |work=Metacritic |publisher=CBS |accessdate=May 30, 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527025924/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/x-men-days-of-future-past |archive-date=May 27, 2017}}</ref>\n| A<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''Deadpool''\n| 85% (338 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/deadpool/ |title=Deadpool |accessdate=November 21, 2019 |work=Rotten Tomatoes |publisher=Fandango Media |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103230623/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/deadpool |archive-date=January 3, 2017}}</ref>\n| 65 (49 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/deadpool |title=Deadpool |work=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=February 16, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216051243/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/deadpool |archive-date=February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n| A<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''X-Men: Apocalypse''\n| 47% (337 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/x_men_apocalypse/ |title=X-Men: Apocalypse |accessdate=November 21, 2019 |work=Rotten Tomatoes |publisher=Fandango Media |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526144757/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/x_men_apocalypse |archive-date=May 26, 2017}}</ref>\n| 52 (48 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/x-men-apocalypse |title=X-Men: Apocalypse |work=Metacritic |accessdate=June 26, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628085117/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/x-men-apocalypse |archive-date=June 28, 2016}}</ref>\n| A\u2212<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''Logan''\n| 93% (405 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/logan_2017/ |title=Logan |accessdate=November 21, 2019 |work=Rotten Tomatoes |publisher=Fandango Media |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525144014/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/logan_2017/ |archive-date=May 25, 2017}}</ref>\n| 77 (51 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/logan-2017 |title=Logan |work=Metacritic |accessdate=November 21, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317031223/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/logan-2017 |archive-date=March 17, 2017}}</ref>\n| A\u2212<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''Deadpool 2''\n| 84% (402 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/deadpool_2 |title=Deadpool 2 (2018) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=Fandango Media |accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref>\n| 66 (51 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/deadpool-2 |title=Deadpool 2 reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref>\n| A<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''Dark Phoenix''\n| 23% (357 reviews)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dark_phoenix/ |title=Dark Phoenix |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]] |access-date=November 21, 2019}}</ref>\n| 43 (52 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/dark-phoenix |title=Dark Phoenix |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref>\n| B\u2212<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|}\n\n===Legacy===\n[[Wesley Morris]] of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' praised the first three ''X-Men'' films as \"more than a cash-guzzling wham-bang Hollywood franchise ... these three movies sport philosophy, ideas, a telethon-load of causes, and a highly elastic us-versus-them allegory.\" Morris praised ''X-Men: The Last Stand'' for \"put[ting] the heroes of a mighty summer blockbuster in a rare mortal position. Realism at this time of year? How unorthodox!\"<ref>{{cite web |first=Wesley |last=Morris |title=X-Men: The Last Stand Movie Review |work=Boston Globe |date=May 5, 2006 |url=https://www.boston.com/movies/display?display=movie&id=6883 |accessdate=August 3, 2007 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070906221707/http://www.boston.com/movies/display?display=movie&id=6883 |archive-date=September 6, 2007}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] gave the films mostly positive reviews, but criticized them for the amount of mutants, stating \"their powers are so various and ill-matched that it's hard to keep them all on the same canvas.\"<ref>{{cite web |author-link=Roger Ebert |first=Roger |last=Ebert |title=X-Men: The Last Stand (PG-13) |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=May 26, 2006 |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20060525/REVIEWS/60509005/1023 |accessdate=August 2, 2007 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130310205908/http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20060525%2FREVIEWS%2F60509005%2F1023 |archive-date=March 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe first two films were highly praised due to their [[wikt:cerebral|cerebral]] tone. However, when director Bryan Singer left the series, many criticized his successor, Brett Ratner. Colin Colvert of the ''[[Star Tribune]]'' felt \"Singer's sensitivity to [the discrimination themes] made the first two ''X-Men'' films surprisingly resonant and soulful for comic-based summer extravaganzas ... Singer is adept at juggling large casts of three-dimensional characters, Ratner makes shallow, unimaginative bang-ups.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=Colin |last=Colvert |title=Movie review: 'X-Men' trilogy goes down in flames |work=[[Star Tribune]] |date=May 25, 2006 |url=http://www.startribune.com/412/story/455017.html |accessdate=August 2, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070814022350/http://www.startribune.com/412/story/455017.html |archive-date=August 14, 2007}}</ref> [[James Berardinelli]] felt, \"''X-Men: The Last Stand'' isn't as taut or satisfying as ''X-Men 2'', but it's better constructed and better paced than the original ''X-Men''. The differences in quality between the three are minor, however; despite the change in directors, there seems to be a single vision.\"<ref>{{cite web |author-link=James Berardinelli |first=James |last=Berardinelli |title=X-Men: The Last Stand |work=Reelviews |year=2006 |url=http://preview.reelviews.net/movies/x/x-men3.html |accessdate=August 2, 2007}}</ref> David Denby of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' praised \"the liquid beauty and the poetic fantasy of Singer's work\", but called Ratner's film \"a crude synthesizer of comedy and action tropes.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=David |last=Denby |author-link=David Denby |work=The New Yorker |title=Violent Times |date=June 5, 2006 |url=https://www.newyorker.com/archive/2006/06/05/060605crci_cinema |accessdate=August 3, 2007 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929170122/http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2006/06/05/060605crci_cinema |archive-date=September 29, 2007}}</ref> Singer's third film in the series, ''X-Men: Days of Future Past'' was also well received. Alonso Duralde of ''[[The Wrap]]'' felt that \"Singer keeps things moving along briskly enough that you can just go along with the ride of Superhero Stuff without getting bogged down\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/x-men-days-future-past-review-mutant-sage-crosses-streams-hugh-jackman/ |title=X-Men: Days of Future Past Review: Mutant Saga Crosses the Stream of Its Old-School and Newer Characters |date=May 12, 2014 |accessdate=May 30, 2014 |last=Duralde |first=Alonso |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140524045418/http://www.thewrap.com/x-men-days-future-past-review-mutant-sage-crosses-streams-hugh-jackman/ |archive-date=May 24, 2014}}</ref> ''Spider-Man'' director [[Sam Raimi]] said he was a fan of the series, particularly Singer's films.<ref>{{cite web |first=Brian |last=Cronin |title=Guest Spot: Rohan Williams Interviews Sam Raimi and Rob Tapert (Part 1) |work=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=November 28, 2007 |url=http://goodcomics.comicbookresources.com/2007/11/28/guest-spot-rohan-williams-interviews-sam-raimi-and-rob-tapert-part-1/ |accessdate=November 28, 2007 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071206093132/http://goodcomics.comicbookresources.com/2007/11/28/guest-spot-rohan-williams-interviews-sam-raimi-and-rob-tapert-part-1/ |archive-date=December 6, 2007}}</ref> Film historian [[Kim Newman]] also tonally compared ''[[Batman Begins]]'' to Singer's films.<ref>{{cite web |author-link=Kim Newman |first=kim |last=Newman |title=Batman Begins (12A) |work=Empire |url=https://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?DVDID=11299 |accessdate=August 3, 2007 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930185128/http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?DVDID=11299 |archive-date=September 30, 2007}}</ref> ''Logan'' was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]].<ref>{{cite web |URL=http://www.vulture.com/2018/01/logan-oscar-nomination.html |title=Logan's Oscar Nomination Is a Significant Breakthrough |last=Riesman |first=Abraham |date=January 23, 2018 |accessdate=August 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThere was criticism of the large cast, and the limited screentime for all of them. Richard George of [[IGN]] reacted well to the depictions of Wolverine, Professor X, Magneto, Jean Grey, Storm, William Stryker, Mystique, Beast and Nightcrawler; however, George thought many of the younger X-Men characters, such as Rogue, Iceman, Pyro, Angel and Kitty Pryde were \"adjectiveless teenager[s]\", and was disappointed by Cyclops' characterization. He observed the filmmakers were \"big fans of silent henchmen\", due to the small roles of the various villainous mutants; such as [[Lady Deathstrike]] and Psylocke.<ref name=\"george\">{{cite web |first=Richard |last=George |title=X-Men in Film |work=IGN.com |date=December 15, 2006 |url=http://comics.ign.com/articles/751/751277p1.html |accessdate=August 3, 2007 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070817102020/http://comics.ign.com/articles/751/751277p1.html |archive-date=August 17, 2007}}</ref> While Jesse Schedeen of IGN, stated that the continuity of the films doesn't make sense with dead characters returning with zero or little explanation, different versions of the same character appearing across multiple films and plot points that are conveniently ignored in later films. He also criticized 20th Century Fox for not mapping out the series from the beginning.<ref>{{cite web |URL=http://m.ign.com/articles/2017/03/23/17-reasons-x-men-movie-continuity-makes-no-sense |date=March 23, 2017 |title=17 Reasons X-Men Movie Continuity Makes No Sense |last=Schedeen |first=Jesse |accessdate=August 24, 2018}}</ref> In his review of [[Dark Phoenix (film)|''Dark Phoenix'']], [[Joe Morgenstern]] of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' characterized the entire X-Men film series as being a \"notoriously erratic franchise.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Morgenstern |first1=Joe |date=June 7, 2019 |title=\u2018Avengers: Endgame\u2019 Review: A Marvelous Wrap  |url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/dark-phoenix-review-taking-flight-then-crashing-and-burning-11559848050 |journal=The Wall Street Journal |volume=273 |issue=132 |pages=A11 |access-date=June 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center; width:100%;\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:left; | Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Format\n! scope=\"col\"| Release date\n! scope=\"col\"| Films\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''X-Men Double Pack''\n| VHS\n| November 10, 2003\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''X-Men'', ''X2''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''X-Men Collection''\n| rowspan=\"4\" | DVD\n| November 25, 2003\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''X-Men'', ''X2''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''X-Men Trilogy''\n| October 3, 2006\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''X-Men'', ''X2'', ''X-Men: The Last Stand''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''The Ultimate Heroes Collection\n| October 16, 2007\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''[[Daredevil (film)|Daredevil]]'', ''[[Elektra (2005 film)|Elektra]]'', ''Fantastic Four'' (2005), ''X-Men''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''Marvel Heroes''\n| May 13, 2008\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''Daredevil'', ''Elektra'', ''Fantastic Four'' (2005), ''[[Fantastic Four: Rise of the Silver Surfer]]'', ''X-Men'', ''X2'', ''X-Men: The Last Stand''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''X-Men Trilogy''\n| Blu-ray\n| April 29, 2009\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''X-Men'', ''X2'', ''X-Men: The Last Stand''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''X-Men Quadrilogy''\n| rowspan=\"4\" | DVD, Blu-ray\n| October 19, 2009\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''X-Men'', ''X2'', ''X-Men: The Last Stand'', ''X-Men Origins: Wolverine''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''X-Men: The Ultimate Collection''\n| October 31, 2011\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''X-Men'', ''X2'', ''X-Men: The Last Stand'', ''X-Men Origins: Wolverine'', ''X-Men: First Class''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''X-Men and the Wolverine: Adamantium Collection''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |December 3, 2013\n| style=\"text-align:left\" rowspan=\"2\" | ''X-Men'', ''X2'', ''X-Men: The Last Stand'', ''X-Men Origins: Wolverine'', ''X-Men: First Class'', ''The Wolverine''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''X-Men: The Adamantium Collection''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''X-Men: Experience Collection''\n| rowspan=\"11\" | Blu-ray\n| May 6, 2014\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''X-Men'', ''X2'', ''X-Men: The Last Stand'', ''X-Men: First Class''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''Wolverine Double Feature''\n| October 7, 2014\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''X-Men Origins: Wolverine'', ''The Wolverine''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''X-Men: The Cerebro Collection''\n| November 10, 2014\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''X-Men'', ''X2'', ''X-Men: The Last Stand'', ''X-Men Origins: Wolverine'', ''X-Men: First Class'', ''The Wolverine'', ''X-Men: Days of Future Past''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" |  ''X-Men Trilogy''\n| April 19, 2016\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''X-Men'', ''X2'', ''X-Men: The Last Stand''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''X-Men: 2-Film Collection''\n| April 19, 2016\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''X-Men: First Class'', ''X-Men: Days of Future Past''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''X-Men: Beginnings Trilogy''\n| October 4, 2016\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''X-Men: First Class'', ''X-Men: Days of Future Past'', ''X-Men: Apocalypse''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''X-Men Collection''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | November 1, 2016\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''X-Men'', ''X2'', ''X-Men: The Last Stand'', ''X-Men: First Class'', ''X-Men: Days of Future Past'', ''X-Men: Apocalypse''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''X-Men Universe: 9-Film Bundle''\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''X-Men'', ''X2'', ''X-Men: The Last Stand'', ''X-Men Origins: Wolverine'', ''X-Men: First Class'', ''The Wolverine'', ''X-Men: Days of Future Past'', ''Deadpool'', ''X-Men: Apocalypse''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''Wolverine: 2-Movie Collection''\n| January 10, 2017\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''X-Men Origins: Wolverine'', ''The Wolverine''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''Deadpool 1 & 2: The Complete Collection (For Now)''\n| August 21, 2018\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''Deadpool'', ''Deadpool 2''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''X-Men: 3-Film Collection''\n| September 29, 2018\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''X-Men'', ''X2'', ''X-Men: The Last Stand''\n|}\n\nAs of May 2014, the DVD and Blu-ray sales of the first six films in the United States earned more than $620{{nbsp}}million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/markhughes/2014/05/28/review-days-of-future-past-proves-x-men-still-among-the-best/ |title=Review \u2013 Days of Future Past Proves X-Men Still Among the Best |last=Hughes |first=Mark |date=May 28, 2014 |accessdate=August 11, 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812204850/http://www.forbes.com/sites/markhughes/2014/05/28/review-days-of-future-past-proves-x-men-still-among-the-best/ |archive-date=August 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Cancelled projects==\nIn March 2019, [[The Walt Disney Company]] acquired the film rights for the X-Men after the [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|acquisition deal]] of [[21st Century Fox]] was completed.<ref name=\"disneycloses\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disney-closes-fox-deal-creating-global-content-powerhouse-1174498 |title=Disney Closes $71.3{{nbsp}}Billion Fox Deal, Creating Global Content Powerhouse |date=March 19, 2019 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=March 20, 2019}}</ref> The films in development under 20th Century Fox were placed \"on hold\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/fox-marvel-movies-status-update-lauren-shuler-donner/ |title=Lauren Shuler Donner Confirms Fox Marvel Movies on Hold; Wants 'X-Men' Franchise to \"Evolve\" |last=Chitwood |first=Adam |date=February 5, 2019 |website=/Film |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190205233839/http://collider.com/fox-marvel-movies-status-update-lauren-shuler-donner/ |archive-date=February 5, 2019 |url-status=live |accessdate=February 5, 2019}}</ref> and eventually cancelled by Disney. Any future X-Men films will be produced by [[Marvel Studios]], with ''The New Mutants'' serving as the final film in 20th Century Fox's ''X-Men'' film series.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://uproxx.com/hitfix/dark-phoenix-final-x-men-movie/ |title=It Sounds Like Dark Phoenix is Going to Be Fox's Final X-Men Movie |date=April 3, 2019 |last=Husband |first=Andrew |accessdate=April 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/disney-confirms-x-men-sendoff-new-mutants-still-on-release-slate |title=Disney confirms X-Men team getting 'perfect sendoff,' New Mutants still on release slate |website=[[Syfy]] |last=Long |first=Christian |date=April 3, 2019 |accessdate=April 6, 2019}}</ref> Future films based on the X-Men franchise planned by Fox before the acquisition included:\n\n* '''X-Men / Fantastic Four / Daredevil crossover film''': In 2010, [[Zack Stentz]] and [[Ashley Edward Miller]] were to co-write a film featuring the X-Men, the [[Fantastic Four]], [[Daredevil (Marvel Comics character)|Daredevil]] and [[Deadpool]]. The plot revolved around a superhero registration act, pitting various characters on opposite sides of the conflict similar to the ''[[Civil War (comics)|Civil War]]'' story arc. [[Paul Greengrass]] had been approached to serve as director, though scheduling conflicts placed the project indefinitely on hold.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qz-hDnvYP8w|title=Zack Stentz, Writer of Rim of the World, Thor, X-Men First Class|first=|last=Kevin Smith|date=May 30, 2019|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> [[Warren Ellis]] worked separately on another draft of the script.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://link.hollywoodreporter.com/view/518d53f9191b2a646dbcdf4da7e0u.1ih/31f40dbd|title=X-Men's Secret War|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first1=Aaron|last1=Couch|first2=Borys|last2=Kit|first3=Graeme|last3=McMillan|date=June 1, 2019|accessdate=July 1, 2019}}</ref>\n* '''X-Force''': In July 2013, [[Jeff Wadlow]] was hired to write and direct a film adaptation of the ''X-Men'' spin-off comic-book series ''[[X-Force]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/kick-ass-2-filmmaker-tackling-584655 |title='Kick-Ass 2' Filmmaker Tackling Fox's 'X-Force' (Exclusive) |date=July 13, 2013 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |last=Kit |first=Borys |accessdate=May 26, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170501234218/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/kick-ass-2-filmmaker-tackling-584655 |archive-date=May 1, 2017}}</ref> [[Mark Millar]], the creative consultant for 20th Century Fox's Marvel Comics based films at the time, stated that the film would feature five characters as protagonists.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://spinoff.comicbookresources.com/2013/07/24/foxs-x-force-movie-will-feature-five-person-team-millar-teases/ |title=Fox's 'X-Force' Movie Will Feature Five-Person Team, Millar Teases |last=Josh |first=Wigler |date=July 24, 2013 |access-date=May 26, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627102611/http://spinoff.comicbookresources.com/2013/07/24/foxs-x-force-movie-will-feature-five-person-team-millar-teases/ |archive-date=June 27, 2015}}</ref> After the release of ''Deadpool'', Ryan Reynolds said that Deadpool would appear in the film.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2016/02/09/getting-an-x-force-movie-made-is-ryan-reynolds-next-priority |title=Getting an X-Force Movie Made Is Ryan Reynolds' Next Priority |date=February 9, 2016 |last=Osborn |first=Alex |work=IGN.com |access-date=May 26, 2017}}</ref> By May 2016, Simon Kinberg was in the process of rewriting the script.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/x-force-movie-update-x-23/ |title=X-Force Movie: Simon Kinberg Writing; Will We See X-23? |last=Angie |first=Han |date=May 17, 2016 |access-date=May 26, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226161604/http://www.slashfilm.com/x-force-movie-update-x-23/ |archive-date=February 26, 2017}}</ref> In February 2017, [[Joe Carnahan]] had signed on as director, as well as a co-writer with Reynolds.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lrmonline.com/news/x-force-film-gets-a-director-reynolds-to-co-write |title=X-Force Film Gets A Director & Reynolds To Co-Write |last=Drew |first=Carlton |date=February 23, 2017 |accessdate=May 26, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226131136/http://lrmonline.com/news/x-force-film-gets-a-director-reynolds-to-co-write |archive-date=February 26, 2017}}</ref> By September of the same year, Drew Goddard was attached to write and direct. [[Rhett Reese]] said the film would be a R-rated take on the X-Men.<ref>{{cite web |last=Jacob Oller |title=X-Force Will Be R-Rated, 'Raunchier' Take On X-Men Says Deadpool 2 Writer |date=May 18, 2018 |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/x-force-will-be-r-rated-raunchier-take-on-x-men-says-deadpool-2-write |accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref> Kinberg, Reynolds and Donner were later slated to serve as producers for the film.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/09/x-force-drew-goddard-director-ryan-reynolds-x-men-cable-josh-brolin-fox-1202163706/amp/ |title=Drew Goddard To Direct, Write 'X-Force' With Deadpool Leading Black Ops Force At Fox |last=Fleming Jr. |first=Mike |date=September 7, 2017 |website=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=September 7, 2017}}</ref> In September 2018, Kinberg said that Goddard would begin work on the script after the release of ''[[Bad Times at the El Royale]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Barnett |first=Brian |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/09/27/gambit-movie-will-be-a-romantic-comedy-says-producer |title=''Gambit'' Will Be A Romantic Comedy, Says Producer |date=September 27, 2018 |work=[[IGN]] |accessdate=September 27, 2018}}</ref>\n* '''''[[Gambit (unproduced film)|Gambit]]''''': In October 2014, Josh Zetumer was hired to write the screenplay for a film about the character [[Gambit (comics)|Gambit]], based on the treatment by comic-book writer Chris Claremont. In June 2015, [[Rupert Wyatt]] was then hired to direct but left in September due to schedule conflicts.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://screencrush.com/gambit-solo-movie-loses-director-rupert-wyatt/ |title='Gambit' Solo Movie Loses Director Rupert Wyatt |work=Screen Crush |last=Hayes |first=Britt |date=September 16, 2015 |accessdate=September 16, 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150919133948/http://screencrush.com/gambit-solo-movie-loses-director-rupert-wyatt/ |archive-date=September 19, 2015}}</ref> In November, [[Doug Liman]] was in final negotiations to direct the film.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/channing-tatums-gambit-finds-new-828590 |title=Doug Liman Near Deal to Direct Channing Tatum's 'Gambit' |work=The Hollywood Reporter |last=Kit |first=Borys |date=November 12, 2015 |accessdate=May 26, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213192714/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/channing-tatums-gambit-finds-new-828590 |archive-date=February 13, 2017}}</ref> Liman left the film in August 2016, to direct ''[[Justice League Dark#Live-action|Justice League Dark]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/doug-liman-justice-league-dark-dc-warner-bros-1201838857/ |title=Doug Liman to Direct 'Dark Universe' for DC, Warner Bros. (EXCLUSIVE) |last=Kroll |first=Justin |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=August 24, 2016 |accessdate=May 26, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202231437/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/doug-liman-justice-league-dark-dc-warner-bros-1201838857/ |archive-date=December 2, 2016}}</ref> By October, [[Gore Verbinski]] had signed on as director, while Zetumer continued to work on the script.<ref>{{cite web |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/channing-tatum-gambit-to-open-valentines-day-2019-release-1202187558/amp/ |title=''Gambit'' Starring Channing Tatum Will Release Valentines Day 2019 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=October 12, 2017 |accessdate=October 12, 2017}}</ref> In January 2018, Verbinski departed the film due to scheduling issues.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fleming Jr |first=Mike |url=https://deadline.com/2018/01/gambit-movie-gore-verbinski-leaves-director-1202240851/ |title=Gore Verbinski Pulls Off Of ''Gambit'' |date=January 11, 2018 |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=January 11, 2018}}</ref> Kinberg stated that the film was intended to be the start of multiple installments focusing on Gambit, and that the final script had been completed by May 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://screencrush.com/kinberg-gambit-update-same-old-same-old/ |title='X-Men' Producer Says 'Gambit' Will Begin Filming Next Year |last=Britt |first=Hayes |date=February 24, 2017 |accessdate=May 26, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170507223355/http://screencrush.com/kinberg-gambit-update-same-old-same-old/ |archive-date=May 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Carras |first=Christi |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/simon-kinberg-gambit-channing-tatum-1202810555/ |title=Producer Simon Kinberg Hopes to Start Filming Channing Tatum's ''Gambit'' This Summer |date=May 14, 2018 |work=Variety |accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Twenty Nineteen\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/dark-phoenix-alita-battle-angel-deadpool-gambit-release-date-changes-1202473229/ |title='Alita' Flies Out Of Christmas, 'Dark Phoenix' To Rise Summer, 'Deadpool 2' Re-release Hits Sked, 'Gambit' Now 2020 \u2013 Fox Date Changes |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=September 28, 2018 |accessdate=September 28, 2018}}</ref> By January 2019, Tatum was in early negotiations to direct the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/channing-tatum-exits-uta-management-360-1202538067/ |title=Channing Tatum Exits UTA And Management 360 |last=Fleming Jr |first=Mike |date=January 18, 2019 |accessdate=April 8, 2019}}</ref> By March, Kinberg was revealed to be co-screenwriter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/gambit-update-simon-kinberg-fox-films-evaluated-merger-1203174154/ |title=Gambit Update: Simon Kinberg Says Fox Films Are Being \u2018Evaluated\u2019 Since Disney Merger |last=Nissen |first=Daniel |date=March 27, 2019 |accessdate=April 8, 2019}}</ref> The film was set to star [[Channing Tatum]] in the lead role with Donner, Kinberg, Tatum and [[Reid Carolin]] attached as producers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2014/10/channing-tatum-gambit-marvel-comics-x-men-josh-zetumer-1201268949/ |title=Channing Tatum's 'X-Men' Character 'Gambit' Spinoff Moving Forward |last=Fleming Jr. |first=Mike |website=Deadline Hollywood |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102082411/https://deadline.com/2014/10/channing-tatum-gambit-marvel-comics-x-men-josh-zetumer-1201268949/ |archive-date=November 2, 2014}}</ref> In May 2019, the film was removed from the release schedule.<ref name=\"DisneyMay2019ScheduleUpdate\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/gambit-movie-dead/ |title=\u2018Gambit\u2019 Is Dead; Disney Drops the X-Men Spinoff from the Schedule |website=[[Collider]] |last=Goldberg |first=Matt |date=May 7, 2019 |accessdate=May 7, 2019 |archive-url=http://www.webcitation.org/78CX9lkfJ |archive-date=May 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n*'''The New Mutants sequels''': In December 2016, Boone stated that he pitched to 20th Century Fox for a [[New Mutants]] spin-off film encompassed three films, that would build upon each other and the ''X-Men'' franchise. In October 2017, he said that there would be sequels to the film, with the first featuring [[Warlock (New Mutants)|Warlock]] and [[Karma (comics)|Karma]], joining the team.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hood |first=Cooper |url=https://screenrant.com/new-mutants-sequels-warlock-karma/ |title=Warlock and Karma Will Be In ''New Mutants 2'' |date=October 13, 2017 |work=Screen Rant |accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref> He added that each film would explore a different style within the horror genre.<ref>{{cite web |last=Joseph |first=Matt |url=https://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/new-mutants-will-kick-off-trilogy-distinct-horror-movies-says-josh-boone/ |title=Josh Boone says ''New Mutants'' Will Kick Off A Trilogy Of Horror Films |date=October 13, 2017 |work=We Got This Covered |accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref>\n* '''Alpha Flight and Exiles''': In February 2017, Kinberg stated that [[Alpha Flight]] and the [[Exiles (Marvel Comics)|Exiles]] were characters being developed for film adaptation.<ref name=\"Perris\" /><ref name=\"flickeringmyth.com\" />\n* '''X-23''': In February 2017, James Mangold stated that with the introduction of Laura Kinney / X-23 in ''Logan'', there was a possibility that the character would appear in future films.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/james-mangold-wants-make-x-23-film-will-work-hugh-jackman/ |title=James Mangold Wants To Make An X-23 Film, Will Work With Hugh Jackman Again |date=February 12, 2017 |work=Wegotthiscovered.com}}</ref> Later that month, Kinberg said that a film for the character was in development.<ref name=\"Perris\">{{cite web |url=http://heroichollywood.com/logan-exiles-alpha-flight-x-men/ |title='Logan' Producer Simon Kinberg Eyeing 'Exiles' & 'Alpha Flight' For Future 'X-Men' Projects |last=Perris |first=Sebastian |date=February 24, 2017 |accessdate=May 24, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518214215/http://heroichollywood.com/logan-exiles-alpha-flight-x-men/ |archive-date=May 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"flickeringmyth.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2017/03/simon-kinberg-teases-alpha-flight-and-exiles-for-future-x-men-movies/ |title=Simon Kinberg teases Alpha Flight and Exiles for future X-Men movies |date=March 3, 2017 |accessdate=May 24, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518213816/https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2017/03/simon-kinberg-teases-alpha-flight-and-exiles-for-future-x-men-movies/ |archive-date=May 18, 2017}}</ref> By October of the same year, the script was being co-written by Mangold and [[Craig Kyle]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/logan-hugh-jackman-laura-movie-recasting-wolverine-1051147 |title='Logan' Team on Dreaming Up a 'Laura' Spinoff and Finding the Drama in Wolverine's Goodbye |last=Couch |first=Aaron |date=October 24, 2017 |accessdate=January 4, 2018}}</ref>\n* '''Multiple Man''': In November 2017, a film centering around [[Jamie Madrox|Multiple Man]] was in development with [[James Franco]] starring in the lead role. [[Allan Heinberg]] was attached as screenwriter, with Kinberg and Franco as producers.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fleming Jr |first=Mike |url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/james-franco-multiple-man-simon-kinberg-wonder-woman-allan-heinberg-fox-marvel-hero-1202209591/amp/ |title=James Franco, Simon Kinberg and Allan Heinberg Team Up For Marvel's ''Multiple Man Film'' |date=November 16, 2017 |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref>\n* '''Kitty Pryde''': In January 2018, Tim Miller was announced to be directing a film centered around [[Kitty Pryde]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/kitty-pryde-movie-tim-miller-fox-disney/ |title=Tim Miller Developing Solo 'Kitty Pryde' Movie at Fox |last=Trumbore |first=Dave |date=January 9, 2018 |work=Collider |accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> In February 2018, [[Brian Michael Bendis]] was hired to write the script.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kit |first1=Borys |last2=Couch |first2=Aaron |date=February 12, 2018 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/x-men-spinoff-kitty-pryde-movie-works-deadpool-director-1084163 |title=''X-Men'' Spinoff: Kitty Pryde Movie In The Works With Tim Miller And Brian Michael Bendis |work=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n* '''''Deadpool 3''''': In November 2016, plans began for a third Deadpool film.<ref name=\"Foxs-X-Men\" /> Rhett Reese and Paul Wernick stated the film would enter production after the untitled X-Force film,<ref>{{cite web |last=Matt Morrison |title=X-Force Gives A Much-Needed Break For Writers To Figure Out Deadpool 3 |date=May 17, 2018 |url=https://screenrant.com/deadpool-3-writers-x-force-break/ |accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref> with Ryan Reynolds and [[Morena Baccarin]] reprising their roles. Production was planned to take place in [[Atlanta]], Georgia.<ref>{{cite web |last=Prasad |first=R.A |url=https://pursuenews.com/deadpool-3-is-in-active-development-filming-location-reportedly-revealed/ |title=''Deadpool 3'' Is In Active Development, Filming Location Reportedly Revealed |date=August 2, 2018 |work=PursueNews |accessdate=August 6, 2018}}</ref> After the [[acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney]] was announced in December 2017 and completed in March 2019, Disney CEO [[Bob Iger]] said that Deadpool would be integrated with the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe|MCU]] under Disney, with Reynolds expected to reprise his role.<ref name=\"DisneyFoxMCU\">{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/disney-fox-deal-bob-iger-digital-future-hulu-and-2b-cost-savings-1202226884/|title=Disney-Fox Deal: Bob Iger Discusses Digital Future, James Murdoch, Hulu and $2B Cost Savings|last=White|first=Peter|last2=Hayes|first2=Dade|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 14, 2017|access-date=December 16, 2017|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6vk3zBc4n?url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/disney-fox-deal-bob-iger-digital-future-hulu-and-2b-cost-savings-1202226884/|archive-date=December 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"MCUDeadpoolTHR\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/deadpool-will-stay-r-rated-fox-disney-merger-1067651|title='Deadpool' Can Stay R-Rated at Disney, Says Bob Iger|last=Couch|first=Aaron|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 14, 2017|access-date=December 16, 2017|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6vk4DhgDC?url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/deadpool-will-stay-r-rated-fox-disney-merger-1067651|archive-date=December 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''Once Upon a Deadpool'' version of ''[[Deadpool 2]]'' (2018) was being watched carefully by Disney and Marvel Studios to see whether it might inform how they could approach the character and integrate him into the PG-13 MCU.<ref name=\"OnceUponADeadpool\">{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/deadpool-ryan-reynolds-disney-pg13-marvel-1202495981/|title='Once Upon A Deadpool': Ryan Reynolds (and Fred Savage) On Franchise's PG-13 Plunge|last=Boucher|first=Geoff|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 5, 2018|access-date=November 6, 2018|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/73k22sXTa?url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/deadpool-ryan-reynolds-disney-pg13-marvel-1202495981/|archive-date=November 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2019, Reese and Wernick said that they were waiting for approval from Marvel Studios to begin production on the third film. Reese said, \"[Deadpool] will live in the R-rated universe that we've created, and hopefully we'll be allowed to play a little bit in the MCU sandbox as well and incorporate him into that.\"<ref name=\"ReeseWernickOct2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/marvel/283809/deadpool-3-update-waiting-marvel-studios-green-light|title=Deadpool 3 Waiting on Marvel Studios Green Light|last=Kaye|first=Don|website=[[Den of Geek]]|date=October 13, 2019|access-date=October 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014001636/https://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/marvel/283809/deadpool-3-update-waiting-marvel-studios-green-light|archive-date=October 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2019, Reynolds confirmed that a third ''Deadpool'' film is in development, though it will be produced by Marvel Studios and it's unknown if it would be a continuation of the first two or if it would be rebooted into the MCU.<ref name=\"ReynoldsDec2019\">{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/marvel/2019/12/27/ryan-reynolds-deadpool-3-marvel-studios/|title=Ryan Reynolds Confirms Deadpool 3 at Marvel Studios|last=Ridgely|first=Charlie|website=ComicBook.com|date=December 27, 2019|accessdate=December 27, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191227145858/https://comicbook.com/marvel/2019/12/27/ryan-reynolds-deadpool-3-marvel-studios/|archivedate=December 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Film}}\n* {{Official site|https://www.foxmovies.com/franchises/x-men}}\n* {{Amg movie|291113|X-Men film series}}\n\n{{X-Men media}}\n{{Marvel Comics films}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:Action film series]]\n[[Category:American film series]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox franchises]]\n[[Category:Marvel Entertainment franchises]]\n[[Category:Science fiction films by series]]\n[[Category:Film series introduced in 2000]]\n[[Category:X-Men (film series)| ]]\n[[Category:Film series based on Marvel Comics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American superhero film franchise}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name                 = X-Men\n| based_on             = {{Based on|[[X-Men]]|[[Stan Lee]]|[[Jack Kirby]]}}\n| image                = X-Men films logo.png\n| caption              = Official film series logo\n| producer             = {{plainlist|\n* [[Lauren Shuler Donner]]\n* [[Simon Kinberg]]\n}}\n| distributor          = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| budget               = '''Total (12 films):'''<br />$1.67{{nbsp}}billion\n| gross                = '''Total (12 films):'''<br />$6.02{{nbsp}}billion\n| border               = no\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Marvel Entertainment]]\n* [[20th Century Fox]]\n* [[The Donners' Company]]\n* [[Bad Hat Harry Productions]] (2000\u20132003, 2011\u20132016)\n}}\n}}\n'''''X-Men''''' is an American superhero [[film series]] based on the fictional [[X-Men|superhero team of the same name]], who originally appeared in a series of comic books created by [[Stan Lee]] and [[Jack Kirby]] and published by [[Marvel Comics]]. [[20th Century Fox]] obtained the film rights to the characters in 1994, and after numerous drafts, [[Bryan Singer]] was hired to direct the [[X-Men (film)|first film]], released in 2000, and its sequel, ''[[X2 (film)|X2]]'' (2003), while [[Brett Ratner]] directed ''[[X-Men: The Last Stand]]'' (2006).\n\nAfter each film outgrossed its predecessor, several [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] films were released, including three Wolverine films (2009\u20132017), four ''X-Men: Beginnings'' films (2011\u20132019), and two ''Deadpool'' films (2016\u20132018), with a film based on ''The New Mutants'' comics set to conclude the series.\n\nWith twelve films released, the ''X-Men'' film series is the [[List of highest-grossing films#Highest-grossing franchises and film series|eighth highest-grossing film series]], having grossed over $6{{nbsp}}billion worldwide.\n{{toc limit|3}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Films==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\" width=100%\n! scope=\"col\" width=16%| Film\n! scope=\"col\" | U.S. release date\n! scope=\"col\" width=10%| Director(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Screenwriter(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Story by\n! scope=\"col\" | Producer(s)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[X-Men (film)|X-Men]]''\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | {{Start date|2000|7|14}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Bryan Singer]]\n| [[David Hayter]]\n| [[Tom DeSanto]] and Bryan Singer\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Lauren Shuler Donner]] and [[Ralph Winter (producer)|Ralph Winter]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[X2 (film)|X2]]''\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | {{Start date|2003|